ilto001083mbp|publisher=Macmillan}}\n* Morison, Samuel Eliot (1969). ''Harrison Gray Otis, 1765\u20131848: The Urbane Federalist''.\n* {{cite book|year=2004|title=Beyond the Founders: New Approaches to the Political History of the Early American Republic|editor=Pasley, Jeffrey L.|display-editors=etal}}\n* {{cite book|year=1969|title=The Early American Party System|editor=Risjord, Norman|publisher=Harper & Row}}\n* {{cite journal|jstor=2204473|title=The Virginia Federalists|journal=The Journal of Southern History|volume=33|issue=4|pages=486\u2013517|last1=Risjord|first1=Norman K.|year=1967|doi=10.2307/2204473}}\n* {{cite book|first=James Rogers|last=Sharp|year=1993|title=American Politics in the Early Republic: The New Nation in Crisis|url=https://archive.org/details/americanpolitics0000shar|url-access=registration|publisher=Yale University Press}} Detailed political history of 1790s.\n* {{cite journal|jstor=4145337|title=Madison v. Hamilton: The Battle over Republicanism and the Role of Public Opinion|journal=The American Political Science Review|volume=98|issue=3|pages=405\u2013424|last1=Sheehan|first1=Colleen A.|year=2004|doi=10.1017/S0003055404001248}}\n* Siemers, David J. ''Ratifying the Republic: Antifederalists and Federalists in Constitutional Time'' (2002).\n* {{cite book|first=Marshall|last=Smelser|year=1968|title=The Democratic Republic 1801\u20131815|url=https://archive.org/details/democraticrepubl00smel|url-access=registration|publisher=New York, Harper & Row}} General survey.\n* Theriault, Sean M. (2006). \"Party Politics during the Louisiana Purchase\". ''Social Science History''. 30(2). pp.&nbsp;293\u2013324. {{doi|10.1215/01455532-30-2-293}}.\n* {{cite book|first=Harry M.|last=Tinkcom|year=1950|title=The Republicans and Federalists in Pennsylvania, 1790\u20131801|url=https://archive.org/details/republicansfeder0000tink|url-access=registration|publisher=Philadelphia}}\n* Viereck, Peter (1956, 2006) ''Conservative Thinkers from John Adams to Winston Churchill''. New Brunswick, NJ: Transaction Publishers.\n* Waldstreicher, David. \"The Nationalization and Racialization of American Politics: 1790\u20131840\" in Shafer, Boyd; Badger, Anthony (eds.) (2001). ''Contesting Democracy: Substance and Structure in American Political History, 1775\u20132000''. pp.&nbsp;37\u201383.\n* Wood, Gordon S. (2009). ''Empire of Liberty: A History of the Early Republic, 1789\u20131815''.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Federalist Party (United States)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080725105911/http://dca.tufts.edu/features/aas/ A New Nation Votes: American Election Returns 1787\u20131825]\n* [https://voteview.com/parties/5000/pro-administration-party Pro-Administration Party ideology over time]\n* [https://voteview.com/parties/1/federalist-party Federalist Party ideology over time]\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{Federalist Party}}\n{{Alexander Hamilton}}\n{{John Jay}}\n{{United States political parties}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1789 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:1824 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct political parties in the United States]]\n[[Category:Federalist Party| ]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1789]]\n[[Category:Political parties disestablished in 1824]]\n", "name_user": "Iamyoursheppard", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed superfluous coma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federalist_Party"}
{"title_page": "David Bradley (English actor)", "text_new": "{{For|the actor who starred in ''Kes''|Dai Bradley}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Bradley\n| image = David Bradley by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption = Bradley at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name = David John Bradley\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1942|4|17}}\n| birth_place = [[York, North Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1971\u2013present\n| spouse = Rosanna Bradley (m.1978)\n| children = 3\n\n}}\n\n'''David John Bradley''' (born 17 April 1942)<ref name=\"Birth details at freebmd.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=El3WrcbBL9MGqwGlGxck0w&scan=1|title=Birth details at freebmd.org.uk|publisher=freebmd.org.uk|date=31 December 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> is an English actor. He is known for playing [[Argus Filch]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]], [[Walder Frey]] in the [[HBO]] fantasy series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' and Abraham Setrakian in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] horror series ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''. He is also an established stage actor with a career that includes a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for his role in a production of ''[[King Lear]]''.\n\nOther acting credits include the [[BBC]] series ''[[Our Friends in the North]]'', the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Broadchurch]]'' (for which he won the best supporting actor award at the [[2014 British Academy Television Awards]]), and the films ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'', ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]'' and ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]''.\n\nIn 2012, he played Solomon in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\". In 2013, Bradley portrayed [[William Hartnell]] in the ''Doctor Who'' docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''. He returned to ''Doctor Who'' portraying the [[First Doctor]] in \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\" and the 2017 Christmas Special \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\". He also portrayed William Hartnell's First Doctor in a series of audio stories released by [[Big Finish Productions|Big Finish]] entitled ''[[Doctor Who: The First Doctor Adventures|The First Doctor Adventures]]'' starting in January 2018.\n\nIn 2018 - 2019, he played Gillenormand in the BBC television miniseries [[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2018 miniseries)|''Les Mis\u00e9rables'']], which was broadcast in the UK between 30 December 2018 and 3 February 2019 and also in the US on [[PBS Masterpiece]] between 14 April and 19 May 2019.hates Birmingham city fc.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born in [[York]], where he attended the [[Catholic]] [[St. George's RC Secondary School|St George's Secondary Modern School]], at which he was a member of the choir. He first performed on stage in musical productions as a member of a youth club and with the Rowntree Youth Theatre. Upon leaving school he completed a five-year apprenticeship with the optical instruments maker [[Cooke, Troughton & Simms]] and he remained with the firm until 1966 when he moved to [[London]] to train as an actor at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]].<ref name=yorkmix>[http://www.yorkmix.com/things-to-do/previews/david-bradley-interview-from-a-york-childhood-to-doctor-who David Bradley Interview: From a York childhood to Doctor Who] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612021012/http://www.yorkmix.com/things-to-do/previews/david-bradley-interview-from-a-york-childhood-to-doctor-who |date=12 June 2015 }}. Retrieved 22 November 2013</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:David Bradley 2009.jpg|right|thumb|Bradley at the ''[[Harry Brown (film)|Harry Brown]]'' premiere in 2009]]\nBradley joined the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] and performed at [[Laurence Olivier]]'s [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre Company]] in the early 1970s.<ref>[http://www.phyllis.demon.co.uk/theatricalia/05nt/nt70s.htm NATIONAL THEATRE: 1970s] ROB WILTON THEATRICALIA. accessed 25 July 2011.</ref> He first appeared on television in 1971, as a police officer in the successful comedy ''[[Nearest and Dearest]]''. He was awarded a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] in 1991 for his supporting role as the Fool in ''[[King Lear]]'' at the Royal National Theatre. He appeared in the Royal National Theatre's 1997 production of ''[[The Homecoming]]'', as well as productions of ''[[The Caretaker]]'' at [[Sheffield Theatres]] and the [[Tricycle Theatre]] from 2006 to 2007. In 2005 he played the title role in [[Nicholas Hynter]]'s production of Henry IV Parts One and Two at the Olivier Theatre, London.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/may/05/theatre1 Henry IV Parts One and Two] Review by Michael Billington, The Guardian, 5 May 2005. Retrieved 29 June 2019</ref>\n\nBradley played fictional [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament Eddie Wells in the 1996 award-winning [[BBC Two]] serial ''[[Our Friends in the North]]''. Also in 1996, he appeared as gangster Alf Black in ''[[Band of Gold (TV series)|Band of Gold]]''. In 1998, he appeared in the BBC adaptation of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]'' as the miserly Sir Pitt Crawley, and ''[[Our Mutual Friend]]'' as the villainous Rogue Riderhood. Other television appearances include the 2001 series ''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]'', directed by [[David Yates]], who would work with Bradley five years later on the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' films]].\n\nFrom 2002\u201304, Bradley starred as Jake in the [[BBC]] comedy series ''[[Wild West (TV series)|Wild West]]''. Bradley acted in the 2004 musical drama serial ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]'' on [[BBC One]]. He appeared in the 2005 BBC drama ''[[Mr. Harvey Lights a Candle]]'', playing the role of a morose coach driver who takes an unruly party of pupils on a trip to [[Salisbury Cathedral]], and the 2006 BBC drama ''[[Sweeney Todd]]''. He had a small role in a 2005 episode of the series ''[[Taggart]]''. In 2003, he played Tom in the ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' episode \"The Green Man\". He appeared as the [[electrolarynx]]-using gangster Stemroach in the BBC comedy series ''[[Ideal (TV series)|Ideal]]'' and as Electric in the BBC's ''[[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]'', as well as the BBC One series ''[[True Dare Kiss]]'' in 2007\u201308.\n\nBradley appeared in the 2002 film ''[[Nicholas Nickleby (2002 film)|Nicholas Nickleby]]'', and had a small role in the 2007 comedy film ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'' as a farmer who illegally hoards weapons. He played [[Cohen the Barbarian]] in a [[Sky One]] adaptation of ''[[The Colour of Magic (TV film)|The Colour of Magic]]'' in 2008.<ref name=SM>{{cite web|url=http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/sundaymercury/features/tm_headline=harry-potter-and-the-magical-midlanders%26method=full%26objectid=19463171%26siteid=50002-name_page.html|author=Roz Laws|title=Harry Potter and the Magical Midlanders|work=[[Sunday Mercury]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=15 June 2007|accessdate=25 February 2009}}</ref> That same year he appeared as Spooner in a production of ''[[No Man's Land (play)|No Man's Land]]'' at the Gate Theatre, Dublin, which later transferred to London's West End.\n\nIn 2009, Bradley appeared as an [[animal rights activist]] in the popular [[BBC]] drama ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'', and appeared in BBC's ''[[The Street (BBC series)|The Street]]'' later that year. Bradley portrayed [[Will Somers]], [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s court fool, in an episode of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[The Tudors]]'' in 2009. In 2010, he appeared in the film ''[[Another Year (2010 film)|Another Year]]'', which earned him a nomination for Best Supporting Actor from the [[London Film Critics Circle Awards]]. In 2011, 2013 and 2016, Bradley appeared as [[Walder Frey|Lord Walder Frey]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.<ref name=\"GoT\">{{cite web|url=http://grrm.livejournal.com/184176.html?thread=11366512#t11366512|author=George R.R. Martin|title=wedding guest|date=24 November 2010|accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Game of Thrones' actor 'loved' doing Red Wedding scene|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/game-thrones-actor-loves-red-wedding-scene-article-1.1408577|website=nydailynews.com|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, it was confirmed that Bradley would appear in the seventh season of the show later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unitedagents.co.uk/david-bradley|title=David Bradley {{!}} United Agents|website=www.unitedagents.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/tv-blogs/game-of-thrones-season-seven-release-date-cast-763459|title=Game of Thrones season 7: release date, cast, trailers, spoilers & more|date=2017-01-18|newspaper=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref>\n\nBradley played Solomon, a ruthless buccaneer, in the 2012 ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\". He previously provided voice work for ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' serial ''[[Death of the Doctor]]''.<ref name=\"who_dinos\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tardistime.com/other-series-7-stars-announced/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120918064332/http://www.tardistime.com/other-series-7-stars-announced/ |archivedate=18 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was announced in January 2013, that Bradley had been cast as actor [[William Hartnell]] in ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]'', a BBC [[docudrama]] about the creation of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963. The special aired in November 2013, adding to the buildup to the [[50th anniversary special (Doctor Who)|50th anniversary episode]] of ''Doctor Who'' later that month.\n\nFrom 2014, Bradley plays Professor Abraham Setrakian, a Holocaust survivor turned vampire hunter in [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s TV series ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fxs-strain-casts-david-bradley-658804|title=FX's 'The Strain' Casts 'Harry Potter's' David Bradley to Replace John Hurt|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Ng|first=Philiana|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=November 22, 2013}}</ref> He will voice the Lord High Admiral Suvarov in the PC RPG ''The Mandate''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1964463742/the-mandate |title=The Mandate by Perihelion Interactive LLC \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bradley was announced a public supporter of Chapel Lane Theatre Company based in [[Stratford-Upon-Avon]], UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chapellanetc.tumblr.com/post/114402571137/new-supporter-david-bradley |title=New Supporter \u2013 David Bradley! |first=Thom |last=Harvey-Ball |date=23 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104020/http://chapellanetc.tumblr.com/post/114402571137/new-supporter-david-bradley |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, in the final episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]] of ''Doctor Who'', \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", Bradley returned to portray the First Doctor, having previously been portrayed by Hartnell, who originally played the character. He reprised this role in the 2017 Christmas special, \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/01/first-look-pictures-first-twelfth-doctors-together-doctor-christmas/ |title=First look pictures of the First and Twelfth Doctors together in the Doctor Who Christmas special |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Reporters |first1=Telegraph }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-02/new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures-tease-history-making-reunion-for-peter-capaldis-doctor |title=New Doctor Who Christmas special pictures tease history-making reunion for Peter Capaldi's Doctor |first=James |last=Gill |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref> This makes him the third actor to play the role in the television programme, after William Hartnell and [[Richard Hurndall]] since the premiere of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963, and at the age of 75, he is the also the oldest actor to play the role of the Doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jul/01/doctor-who-recap-series-36-finale-the-doctor-falls |title=Doctor Who recap: series 36 finale \u2013 The Doctor Falls |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBradley serves as the President of Second Thoughts Drama Group, which performs in and around [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].<ref>[http://www.secondthoughts.org.uk/ Second Thoughts] Our President for several years now has been David Bradley.</ref>  On 17 July 2012, he was awarded an [[Honorary Doctorate]] from the [[University of Warwick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/insite/news/intnews2/hon_graduands |title=Honorary Graduates 2012 |publisher=warwick.ac.uk |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> On 19 November 2015, he was awarded an [[Honorary Doctorate]] from [[York St John University]].\n\nHe is an avid fan of football clubs [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[York City F.C.|York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~2514966,00.html |title=Harry Potter star Bradley: Villa Park is truly magical |publisher=Avfc.co.uk |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=11 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117173840/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~2514966,00.html |archivedate=17 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/02/15/York+Archive/7930752.Potter_star_is_potty_over_York_City_FC/|title=Potter star is potty over York City}}</ref>  On 22 November 2014, he took part in a video paying tribute to Aston Villa on the club's 140th birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~4314881,00.html |title=BAFTA-winner David Bradley on Villa's 140 years |publisher=[[Aston Villa]] |date=22 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201231847/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~4314881,00.html |archivedate=1 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[A Family at War]]''\n| Colin Woodcock\n| Television\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]''\n| German terrorist\n| Television\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Prick Up Your Ears]]''\n| Undertaker\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n| ''[[Between the Lines (TV series)|Between the Lines]]''\n| Sgt. Harry Ross\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Lies and Damned Lies\"\n|-\n| ''[[Screenplay (TV series)|Screenplay]]''\n| Mr Preach\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Bad Girl\"\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1994\n| ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit (TV series)|Martin Chuzzlewit]]''\n| David Crimple\n| Television mini-series\n|-\n| ''[[Performance (British TV series)|Performance]]''\n| Barnadine\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Measure for Measure\"\n|-\n| ''[[Screen Two]]''\n| Headmaster\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Criminal\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1995\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Stanmore\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Hit & Run\"\n|-\n| ''The Vet''\n| Dick Sims\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Relative Vaules\"\n|-\n| rowspan=5|1996\n|''[[In Your Dreams (TV series)|In Your Dreams]]''\n| Tutor\n| Television\n|-\n|''[[Wycliffe (TV series)|Wycliffe]]''\n| Joe Mawnan\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Total Loss\"\n|-\n| ''[[Band of Gold (TV series)|Band of Gold]]''\n| Alf Black\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Hustling\"\n|-\n| ''[[Our Friends in the North]]''\n| Eddie Wells\n| Television\n|-\n| ''[[A Touch of Frost]]''\n| Les James\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Unknown Soldiers\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1997\n| ''[[Reckless (TV serial)|Reckless]]''\n|Arnold Springer\n| Television [[mini-series]]\n|-\n| ''The Moth''\n| Dave Waters\n| [[Television film]] adaptation of [[Catherine Cookson]] novel\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1998\n| ''[[Our Mutual Friend (1998 TV serial)|Our Mutual Friend]]''\n| Rogue Riderhood\n| Television [[mini-series]]\n|-\n| ''[[Tom's Midnight Garden]]''\n| Abel\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Left Luggage (film)|Left Luggage]]''\n| Concierge\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Vanity Fair (1998 TV serial)|Vanity Fair]]''\n| Sir Pitt Crawley\n| Television [[mini-series]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The King Is Alive]]''\n| Henry\n|-\n|\n| ''[https://m.imdb.com/title/tt0231054/ The Wilsons]''\n| Ray Wilson, 6 episodes\n| Television\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2001\n| ''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]''\n| Mr. Broune\n| Television mini-series\n|-\n| ''[[Gabriel and Me]]''\n| Granddad\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Blow Dry]]''\n| Noah Thwaite\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]''\n| rowspan=2|[[Argus Filch]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2002\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)|Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[This Is Not a Love Song]]''\n| Mr Bellamy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Nicholas Nickleby (2002 film)|Nicholas Nickleby]]''\n| Nigel Bray\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wild West (TV series)|Wild West]]''\n| Jake\n| Television Series\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2003\n| ''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n| The Green Man \n| Television Series Season VII ep.1 The Green Man\n|-\n| ''[[Charles II: The Power and the Passion]]''\n| [[Edmund Berry Godfrey|Sir Edmund Berry Godfrey]] \n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004\n| ''[[Exorcist: The Beginning]]''\n| Father Gionetti\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''\n| rowspan=2|Argus Filch\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]''\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2006\n| ''Lycanthropy''\n| Club owner\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ideal (TV series)|Ideal]]''\n| Stemroach\n| Television series\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2007\n| ''[[Hot Fuzz]]''\n| Arthur Webley\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)|Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix]]''\n| Argus Filch\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2008\n| ''[[I Know You Know]]''\n| Mr. Fisher\n|\n|-\n| ''The Daisy Chain''\n| Sean Cryan\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Colour of Magic (TV film)|The Colour of Magic]]''\n| [[Cohen the Barbarian]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2009\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''\n| Argus Filch\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harry Brown (film)|Harry Brown]]''\n| Leonard Attwell\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Tudors]]''\n| [[Will Somers]]\n| Television series\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2010\n| ''[[Another Year (2010 film)|Another Year]]''\n| Ronnie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Holding]]''\n| Cooper\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]''\n| Shansheeth\n|Voice\n|-\n| ''[[New Tricks]]''\n| Simon Beswick / John Plummer\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows&nbsp;\u2013 Part 2]]''\n| Argus Filch\n|\n|-\n| 2011;<br/> 2013;<br/>2016\u20132017\n| ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n| [[Walder Frey]] \n| Television series<br />Guest role; 6 episodes<br />Nominated for Best TV Villain at the 2013 [[IGN|IGN Awards]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2011\n| ''[[Waking the Dead (TV series)|Waking the Dead]]''\n| George Barlow\n| Television series\n|-\n| ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]''\n| Tower Keeper\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2012\n| ''[[World Without End (miniseries)|World Without End]]''\n| Brother Joseph\n| TV miniseries\n|-\n| '' [[Bad Education (TV series)|Bad Education]]''\n| Ennis\n| Television series\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[Prisoners' Wives]]''\n| Francesca's Father\n| Television series\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2012\n| ''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]''\n| Stan Garvey\n| Television series\n|-\n| ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]]''\n| Gardener\n| Television series<br />Episode: \"[[Richard II (2012 film)|Richard II]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[Doctor Who]]''\n| Solomon\n| Television series<br />Episode 7.2 \u2013 \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\"\n|-\n|2012\u20132014\n| ''[[Mount Pleasant (TV series)|Mount Pleasant]]''\n| Charlie\n| Television series\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2013\n|''[[Broadchurch]]''\n| Jack Marshall\n| Television series<br />Won [[British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] award at the [[2014 British Academy Television Awards]]\n|-\n|''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''\n| [[William Hartnell]]\n| Television [[docudrama]]<br />Nominated in Best Single Drama category at the 2014 British Academy Television Awards\n|-\n|''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]''\n| Basil\n|\n|-\n|2014\u20132017\n|''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''\n| Professor Abraham Setrakian\n| Television series\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Silk (TV series)|Silk]]''\n| Judge Reynolds\n| Television series\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2016\n| ''[[The Young Messiah (film)|The Young Messiah]]''\n| Old Rabbi\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Beowulf (TV series)|Beowulf]]''\n| Gorrik\n| Television series\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Medici: Masters of Florence]]''\n| Count Bardi\n| Television series\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Doctor Who]]''\n| [[First Doctor]]\n| Television series \u2013 episode \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\" and Christmas Special \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon A Time]]\"\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''[[Trollhunters: Tales of Arcadia]]''\n| Merlin\n| Netflix animated series, voice\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Britannia (TV series)|Britannia]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sitevolts.com.br/2018/01/29/critica-britannia-primeira-temporada-amazon/|title=Cr\u00edtica {{!}} Britannia \u2013 Primeira Temporada (Amazon)|last=Mariola|first=Tay|date=29 Jan 2018|website=Volts|access-date=February 1, 2018|quote=H\u00e1 at\u00e9 uma participa\u00e7\u00e3o especial de ningu\u00e9m menos que David Bradley, O Walter Frey de Game of Thrones.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202073054/http://sitevolts.com.br/2018/01/29/critica-britannia-primeira-temporada-amazon/|archive-date=2 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Quane\n| S1E5 cameo\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Await Further Instructions''\n| Grandad\n|\n|- \n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2018 miniseries)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''\n| Monsieur Gillenormand\n| Television Series\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[After Life (TV series)|After Life]]''\n| Ray Johnson\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Gangs of London (TV series)|Gangs of London]]''<ref name=\"thr-mar-19\">{{cite web |last1=Ritman |first1=Alex |title=Cinemax/Sky Series 'Gangs of London' Rounds Out Cast |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cinemax-sky-series-gangs-london-rounds-cast-1195601 |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Pinocchio (2021 film)|Pinocchio]]''\n| [[Mister Geppetto]] (voice)\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Doctor Who}}\n*{{IMDb name|103195|David Bradley}}\n* [http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/newsandevents/podcasts/upload/honorary_graduate_2012_-_david_bradley.mp3 Podcast interview with David Bradley on his career] Interview with David Bradley on the occasion of receiving his Honorary Degree from the University of Warwick\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for David Bradley\n|list =\n{{British Academy Television Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{OlivierAward PlayActor SupportingPerformance 1976\u20132000}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Doctor Who|Yorkshire}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, David}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from York]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor BAFTA Award (television) winners]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the actor who starred in ''Kes''|Dai Bradley}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = David Bradley\n| image = David Bradley by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption = Bradley at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name = David John Bradley\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1942|4|17}}\n| birth_place = [[York, North Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1971\u2013present\n| spouse = Rosanna Bradley (m.1978)\n| children = 3\n\n}}\n\n'''David John Bradley''' (born 17 April 1942)<ref name=\"Birth details at freebmd.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=El3WrcbBL9MGqwGlGxck0w&scan=1|title=Birth details at freebmd.org.uk|publisher=freebmd.org.uk|date=31 December 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> is an English actor. He is known for playing [[Argus Filch]] in the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]], [[Walder Frey]] in the [[HBO]] fantasy series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' and Abraham Setrakian in the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] horror series ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''. He is also an established stage actor with a career that includes a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for his role in a production of ''[[King Lear]]''.\n\nOther acting credits include the [[BBC]] series ''[[Our Friends in the North]]'', the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Broadchurch]]'' (for which he won the best supporting actor award at the [[2014 British Academy Television Awards]]), and the films ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'', ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]'' and ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]''.\n\nIn 2012, he played Solomon in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\". In 2013, Bradley portrayed [[William Hartnell]] in the ''Doctor Who'' docudrama ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]''. He returned to ''Doctor Who'' portraying the [[First Doctor]] in \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\" and the 2017 Christmas Special \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\". He also portrayed William Hartnell's First Doctor in a series of audio stories released by [[Big Finish Productions|Big Finish]] entitled ''[[Doctor Who: The First Doctor Adventures|The First Doctor Adventures]]'' starting in January 2018.\n\nIn 2018 - 2019, he played Gillenormand in the BBC television miniseries [[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2018 miniseries)|''Les Mis\u00e9rables'']], which was broadcast in the UK between 30 December 2018 and 3 February 2019 and also in the US on [[PBS Masterpiece]] between 14 April and 19 May 2019.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born in [[York]], where he attended the [[Catholic]] [[St. George's RC Secondary School|St George's Secondary Modern School]], at which he was a member of the choir. He first performed on stage in musical productions as a member of a youth club and with the Rowntree Youth Theatre. Upon leaving school he completed a five-year apprenticeship with the optical instruments maker [[Cooke, Troughton & Simms]] and he remained with the firm until 1966 when he moved to [[London]] to train as an actor at the [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]].<ref name=yorkmix>[http://www.yorkmix.com/things-to-do/previews/david-bradley-interview-from-a-york-childhood-to-doctor-who David Bradley Interview: From a York childhood to Doctor Who] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612021012/http://www.yorkmix.com/things-to-do/previews/david-bradley-interview-from-a-york-childhood-to-doctor-who |date=12 June 2015 }}. Retrieved 22 November 2013</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:David Bradley 2009.jpg|right|thumb|Bradley at the ''[[Harry Brown (film)|Harry Brown]]'' premiere in 2009]]\nBradley joined the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] and performed at [[Laurence Olivier]]'s [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre Company]] in the early 1970s.<ref>[http://www.phyllis.demon.co.uk/theatricalia/05nt/nt70s.htm NATIONAL THEATRE: 1970s] ROB WILTON THEATRICALIA. accessed 25 July 2011.</ref> He first appeared on television in 1971, as a police officer in the successful comedy ''[[Nearest and Dearest]]''. He was awarded a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] in 1991 for his supporting role as the Fool in ''[[King Lear]]'' at the Royal National Theatre. He appeared in the Royal National Theatre's 1997 production of ''[[The Homecoming]]'', as well as productions of ''[[The Caretaker]]'' at [[Sheffield Theatres]] and the [[Tricycle Theatre]] from 2006 to 2007. In 2005 he played the title role in [[Nicholas Hynter]]'s production of Henry IV Parts One and Two at the Olivier Theatre, London.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/may/05/theatre1 Henry IV Parts One and Two] Review by Michael Billington, The Guardian, 5 May 2005. Retrieved 29 June 2019</ref>\n\nBradley played fictional [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament Eddie Wells in the 1996 award-winning [[BBC Two]] serial ''[[Our Friends in the North]]''. Also in 1996, he appeared as gangster Alf Black in ''[[Band of Gold (TV series)|Band of Gold]]''. In 1998, he appeared in the BBC adaptation of ''[[Vanity Fair (novel)|Vanity Fair]]'' as the miserly Sir Pitt Crawley, and ''[[Our Mutual Friend]]'' as the villainous Rogue Riderhood. Other television appearances include the 2001 series ''[[The Way We Live Now (2001 TV serial)|The Way We Live Now]]'', directed by [[David Yates]], who would work with Bradley five years later on the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' films]].\n\nFrom 2002\u201304, Bradley starred as Jake in the [[BBC]] comedy series ''[[Wild West (TV series)|Wild West]]''. Bradley acted in the 2004 musical drama serial ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]'' on [[BBC One]]. He appeared in the 2005 BBC drama ''[[Mr. Harvey Lights a Candle]]'', playing the role of a morose coach driver who takes an unruly party of pupils on a trip to [[Salisbury Cathedral]], and the 2006 BBC drama ''[[Sweeney Todd]]''. He had a small role in a 2005 episode of the series ''[[Taggart]]''. In 2003, he played Tom in the ''[[Midsomer Murders]]'' episode \"The Green Man\". He appeared as the [[electrolarynx]]-using gangster Stemroach in the BBC comedy series ''[[Ideal (TV series)|Ideal]]'' and as Electric in the BBC's ''[[Thieves Like Us (TV Series)|Thieves Like Us]]'', as well as the BBC One series ''[[True Dare Kiss]]'' in 2007\u201308.\n\nBradley appeared in the 2002 film ''[[Nicholas Nickleby (2002 film)|Nicholas Nickleby]]'', and had a small role in the 2007 comedy film ''[[Hot Fuzz]]'' as a farmer who illegally hoards weapons. He played [[Cohen the Barbarian]] in a [[Sky One]] adaptation of ''[[The Colour of Magic (TV film)|The Colour of Magic]]'' in 2008.<ref name=SM>{{cite web|url=http://icbirmingham.icnetwork.co.uk/sundaymercury/features/tm_headline=harry-potter-and-the-magical-midlanders%26method=full%26objectid=19463171%26siteid=50002-name_page.html|author=Roz Laws|title=Harry Potter and the Magical Midlanders|work=[[Sunday Mercury]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=15 June 2007|accessdate=25 February 2009}}</ref> That same year he appeared as Spooner in a production of ''[[No Man's Land (play)|No Man's Land]]'' at the Gate Theatre, Dublin, which later transferred to London's West End.\n\nIn 2009, Bradley appeared as an [[animal rights activist]] in the popular [[BBC]] drama ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'', and appeared in BBC's ''[[The Street (BBC series)|The Street]]'' later that year. Bradley portrayed [[Will Somers]], [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s court fool, in an episode of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[The Tudors]]'' in 2009. In 2010, he appeared in the film ''[[Another Year (2010 film)|Another Year]]'', which earned him a nomination for Best Supporting Actor from the [[London Film Critics Circle Awards]]. In 2011, 2013 and 2016, Bradley appeared as [[Walder Frey|Lord Walder Frey]] in the [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.<ref name=\"GoT\">{{cite web|url=http://grrm.livejournal.com/184176.html?thread=11366512#t11366512|author=George R.R. Martin|title=wedding guest|date=24 November 2010|accessdate=24 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Game of Thrones' actor 'loved' doing Red Wedding scene|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/game-thrones-actor-loves-red-wedding-scene-article-1.1408577|website=nydailynews.com|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, it was confirmed that Bradley would appear in the seventh season of the show later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unitedagents.co.uk/david-bradley|title=David Bradley {{!}} United Agents|website=www.unitedagents.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/tv-blogs/game-of-thrones-season-seven-release-date-cast-763459|title=Game of Thrones season 7: release date, cast, trailers, spoilers & more|date=2017-01-18|newspaper=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-18}}</ref>\n\nBradley played Solomon, a ruthless buccaneer, in the 2012 ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Dinosaurs on a Spaceship]]\". He previously provided voice work for ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' serial ''[[Death of the Doctor]]''.<ref name=\"who_dinos\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tardistime.com/other-series-7-stars-announced/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120918064332/http://www.tardistime.com/other-series-7-stars-announced/ |archivedate=18 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was announced in January 2013, that Bradley had been cast as actor [[William Hartnell]] in ''[[An Adventure in Space and Time]]'', a BBC [[docudrama]] about the creation of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963. The special aired in November 2013, adding to the buildup to the [[50th anniversary special (Doctor Who)|50th anniversary episode]] of ''Doctor Who'' later that month.\n\nFrom 2014, Bradley plays Professor Abraham Setrakian, a Holocaust survivor turned vampire hunter in [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s TV series ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fxs-strain-casts-david-bradley-658804|title=FX's 'The Strain' Casts 'Harry Potter's' David Bradley to Replace John Hurt|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Ng|first=Philiana|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=November 22, 2013}}</ref> He will voice the Lord High Admiral Suvarov in the PC RPG ''The Mandate''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1964463742/the-mandate |title=The Mandate by Perihelion Interactive LLC \u2014 Kickstarter |publisher=Kickstarter.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Bradley was announced a public supporter of Chapel Lane Theatre Company based in [[Stratford-Upon-Avon]], UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chapellanetc.tumblr.com/post/114402571137/new-supporter-david-bradley |title=New Supporter \u2013 David Bradley! |first=Thom |last=Harvey-Ball |date=23 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402104020/http://chapellanetc.tumblr.com/post/114402571137/new-supporter-david-bradley |archivedate=2 April 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, in the final episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 10)|tenth series]] of ''Doctor Who'', \"[[The Doctor Falls]]\", Bradley returned to portray the First Doctor, having previously been portrayed by Hartnell, who originally played the character. He reprised this role in the 2017 Christmas special, \"[[Twice Upon a Time (Doctor Who)|Twice Upon a Time]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2017/07/01/first-look-pictures-first-twelfth-doctors-together-doctor-christmas/ |title=First look pictures of the First and Twelfth Doctors together in the Doctor Who Christmas special |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Reporters |first1=Telegraph }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2017-07-02/new-doctor-who-christmas-special-pictures-tease-history-making-reunion-for-peter-capaldis-doctor |title=New Doctor Who Christmas special pictures tease history-making reunion for Peter Capaldi's Doctor |first=James |last=Gill |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Telegraph}}</ref> This makes him the third actor to play the role in the television programme, after William Hartnell and [[Richard Hurndall]] since the premiere of ''Doctor Who'' in 1963, and at the age of 75, he is the also the oldest actor to play the role of the Doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/jul/01/doctor-who-recap-series-36-finale-the-doctor-falls |title=Doctor Who recap: series 36 finale \u2013 The Doctor Falls |first=Dan |last=Martin |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017 |website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBradley serves as the President of Second Thoughts Drama Group, which performs in and around [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].<ref>[http://www.secondthoughts.org.uk/ Second Thoughts] Our President for several years now has been David Bradley.</ref>  On 17 July 2012, he was awarded an [[Honorary Doctorate]] from the [[University of Warwick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/insite/news/intnews2/hon_graduands |title=Honorary Graduates 2012 |publisher=warwick.ac.uk |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> On 19 November 2015, he was awarded an [[Honorary Doctorate]] from [[York St John University]].\n\nHe is an avid fan of football clubs [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[York City F.C.|York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~2514966,00.html |title=Harry Potter star Bradley: Villa Park is truly magical |publisher=Avfc.co.uk |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=11 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117173840/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~2514966,00.html |archivedate=17 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/archive/2002/02/15/York+Archive/7930752.Potter_star_is_potty_over_York_City_FC/|title=Potter star is potty over York City}}</ref>  On 22 November 2014, he took part in a video paying tribute to Aston Villa on the club's 140th birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~4314881,00.html |title=BAFTA-winner David Bradley on Villa's 140 years |publisher=[[Aston Villa]] |date=22 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201231847/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~4314881,00.html |archivedate=1 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[A Family at War]]''\n| Colin Woodcock\n| Television\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]''\n| German terrorist\n| Television\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Prick Up Your Ears]]''\n| Undertaker\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=2|1992\n| ''[[Between the Lines (TV series)|Between the Lines]]''\n| Sgt. Harry Ross\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Lies and Damned Lies\"\n|-\n| ''[[Screenplay (TV series)|Screenplay]]''\n| Mr Preach\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Bad Girl\"\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1994\n| ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit (TV series)|Martin Chuzzlewit]]''\n| David Crimple\n| Television mini-series\n|-\n| ''[[Performance (British TV series)|Performance]]''\n| Barnadine\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Measure for Measure\"\n|-\n| ''[[Screen Two]]''\n| Headmaster\n| Television \u2013 episode \"Criminal\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|